    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Mountain <sic>Collage</sic>, Cote St Catharine</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Montreal</placeName>
                <date>15 August 1865</date>.</p>
            <p>My dear Sir—</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Yours of <date>13th</date> ult. Found<lb/> me out of town—like
                yourself, I have<lb/> been moving about a little-though<lb/> my circuit has not
                extended to <placeName>Yankee-<lb/>land</placeName>. I was sorry to find you
                had<lb/> been suffering somewhat from lungs<lb/> &amp; throat. Being myself
                somewhat<lb/> delicate in those regions, and a<lb/> fellow feeling making us
                wondrous<lb/> kind, I felt for you, and trust<lb/> that your trip south has
                helped<lb/> completely to restore you. With reference<lb/> to your visit to
                    <placeName>Baltimore</placeName>—had I been<lb/> in time I should have urged you
                to<lb/> continue in office as President of<lb/> your district of Benai Berith, for
                since<lb/> this <sic>organisation</sic>, which I view with<lb/> anything but favor,
                has assumed its<lb/> present proportions, I suppose we<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">must</hi> look after it, lest our humble</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>modest pious &amp;c reform brethren use<lb/> it as a tool—a terrible one too—<lb/>
                against orthodoxy. But I <hi rend="underline">hate</hi> the<lb/> very idea of a
                Jewish secret society—<lb/> no Roman Catholic prelate ever hated<lb/> masonry
                orangeism Ribbonism or any<lb/> other secret ism more than I abhor<lb/> such an
                organisation among us-<lb/> or one at all approaching these Christian<lb/> religious
                or political secret societies.<lb/> But I am not going to trouble you<lb/> with a
                disquisition on them, especially<lb/> as I have an abominable pen which<lb/> will
                stick into the paper, and being<lb/> away from home I cannot change it.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I will, as usual, bring the<lb/> circular you enclosed me
                prominently<lb/> before our small circle here—I fear<lb/> with but little success.
                We have<lb/> too many Polish &amp; German brethren<lb/> for <hi rend="underline"
                    >English</hi>-books—though not<lb/> for synagogue purposes, and I don't<lb/>
                know what I should do without<lb/> them. I sometimes think I am</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>as much a <hi rend="underline"><persName>Pollock</persName></hi> as any of them.<lb/>
                <add>כל המחובר וגו'</add>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I gave <persName>Sarah Joseph</persName> your<lb/> message, and she
                wishes I believe to<lb/> make an enclosure for you in this.<lb/> If she is “up to
                time”, well, if not, you<lb/> will get it another time.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I heard lately that <persName>Mr<lb/> Dd Judah</persName> of
                    <placeName>Baltimore</placeName> has gone the way<lb/> of all the earth. He was
                    <hi rend="underline">nominally</hi><lb/> my agent for that city, and when
                he<lb/> died, held some books or proceeds thereof<lb/> on hand. Would you kindly
                inform me<lb/> as to the best means of proceeding to<lb/> obtain one or the
                other?</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">With best wishes, and hoping<lb/> to hear soon from you</p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">I remain yours faithfully</p>
            <p rend="indent(8)">
                <persName role="author">Abraham de Sola</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
